worker of the highest regard. Michael Jordan and Magic Johnson arguably acc=
omplished more as executives than athletes. Anyway, you get the point: F. S=
cott Fitzgerald=E2=80=99s fortune cookie line about second acts sounds quai=
nt when applied to the architects of the modern zeitgeist.

In some ways, Phoebe Philo fits this archetype, too. During extraordinary r=
uns at Chlo=C3=A9 and C=C3=A9line, she created the much-admired, constantly=
 ripped-off boho chic aesthetic that defined the tastes and wardrobes of st=
ylish wealthy women and eventually filtered down through the rest of the in=
dustry and into the fast-fashion labyrinth. Philo=E2=80=99s vision was fres=
h and iconoclastic, and it was hardly a surprise when she and her husband, =
Max Wigram, decided to strike out on their own. With seed investment from L=
VMH, the two built not only their brand but their own company.

There are extraordinary designers and there are extraordinary entrepreneurs=
, and
the overlap in the Venn diagram is not large=E2=80=94Donna Karan, Ralph Lau=
ren, Coco Chanel, and so forth. And yet, Philo and Wigram set out to not on=
ly disrupt the industry, but also reintroduce a version of her inimitable l=
ook. As Lauren Sherman perspicaciously notes in Phoebe Philo=E2=80=99s Foun=
der Syndrome, it hasn=E2=80=99t always been easy. Phoebe Philo, the brand, =
has encountered all the classic startup headaches=E2=80=94management team e=
xits, logistics issues, challenges in momentum, etcetera. It=E2=80=99s a fa=
scinating tale of ambition and acceptance, and yet another example of a suc=
cessful person=E2=80=99s desire to challenge themselves in full public disp=
lay.

Philo=E2=80=99s successes and tribulations are merely the latest example of=
 how individual choices shape our culture, a leitmotif on display this week=
 at Puck. In Trump=E2=80=99s Magical History Tour, Tara Palmeri explains ho=
w the former president=E2=80=99s rehiring of his favorite Red Bull-chugging
wingman from the 2016 campaign reinforces his ongoing effort to seemingly u=
ndermine his own election chances=E2=80=94go figure. In Blink Twice, Linda,=
 Bill Cohan digs into the financial challenges that Elon Musk and Linda Yac=
carino have created for themselves at Twitter (sorry, X). And in Drahi=E2=
=80=99s Billion-Dollar Question, Marion Maneker explores the Sotheby=E2=80=
=99s owner=E2=80=99s fascinating and complex new financing, and what it mea=
ns not only for his employees but the rival auction houses, artists, and ar=
t market writ large.

But if you only have time to read one thing this weekend, I=E2=80=99d turn =
your attention to Matt Belloni=E2=80=99s excellent piece on the latest twis=
t in the fate of Paramount, itself a saga featuring multiple second-acters.=
 As Matt notes in It=E2=80=99s Go-Shop Time for Paramount, liquor scion and=
 former music mogul Edgar Bronfman Jr. is once again sniffing around the co=
mpany, threatening to outbid Skydance=E2=80=99s
David Ellison and RedBird=E2=80=99s Gerry Cardinale. It=E2=80=99s an extrao=
rdinary late-stage complexifier, which may end up going nowhere, but nevert=
heless demonstrates just how much these businesses turn on the insatiable a=
mbitions of the personalities involved. It=E2=80=99s one of the enduring st=
ories of our time, and precisely what you should expect from Puck.

Have a great weekend,
Jon

