          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">One of the hallmark=
s of truly successful people=E2=80=94financially, creatively, and often bot=
h=E2=80=94is that they are relentless innovators, tinkerers, and restarters=
=2E A guy like <b>Jeffrey Katzenberg </=
b>could have walked away from the movi=
e business after his triumphant run at Disney; instead, co-founded DreamWor=
ks, took it public, sold it to Comcast, and then launched Quibi (no one is =
perfect) before becoming one of the most important fundraisers in Democrati=
c politics. <br/><br/><b>Bill Clinton</b>, likewise, transformed the presid=
ency from a professional capstone into a mere first-act finale. <i>Enormous=
 </i>scandals aside, and against long odds, he reestablished himself as a g=
lobal =C3=A9minence grise with the Clinton Global Initiative. <b>Princess D=
iana </b>leveraged a stint as a beloved royal to fulfill her real calling a=
s a philanthropist and social
worker of the highest regard. <b>Michael Jordan </b>and <b>Magic Johnson </=
b>arguably accomplished more as executives than athletes. Anyway, you get t=
he point: <b>F. Scott Fitzgerald</b>=E2=80=99s fortune cookie line about se=
cond acts sounds quaint when applied to the architects of the modern zeitge=
ist.<br/><br/>In some ways, <b>Phoebe Philo </b>fits this archetype, too. D=
uring extraordinary runs at Chlo=C3=A9 and C=C3=A9line, she created the muc=
h-admired, constantly ripped-off boho chic aesthetic that defined the taste=
s and wardrobes of stylish wealthy women and eventually filtered down throu=
gh the rest of the industry and into the fast-fashion labyrinth. Philo=E2=
=80=99s vision was fresh and iconoclastic, and it was hardly a surprise whe=
n she and her husband, <b>Max Wigram</b>, decided to strike out on their ow=
n. With seed investment from LVMH, the two built not only their brand but t=
heir own company. <br/><br/>There are extraordinary designers and there are=
 extraordinary entrepreneurs, and
the overlap in the Venn diagram is not large=E2=80=94<b>Donna Karan</b>, <b=
>Ralph Lauren</b>, <b>Coco Chanel</b>, and so forth. And yet, Philo and Wig=
ram set out to not only disrupt the industry, but also reintroduce a versio=
n of her inimitable look. As <b>Lauren Sherman </b>perspicaciously notes in=
 <i>Phoebe Philo=E2=80=99s Founder Syndrome</i>, it hasn=E2=80=99t always b=
een easy. Phoebe Philo, the brand, has encountered all the classic startup =
headaches=E2=80=94management team exits, logistics issues, challenges in mo=
mentum, etcetera. It=E2=80=99s a fascinating tale of ambition and acceptanc=
e, and yet another example of a successful person=E2=80=99s desire to chall=
enge themselves in full public display.<br/><br/>Philo=E2=80=99s successes =
and tribulations are merely the latest example of how individual choices sh=
ape our culture, a leitmotif on display this week at Puck. In <i>Trump=E2=
=80=99s Magical History Tour</i>, <b>Tara Palmeri </b>explains how the form=
er president=E2=80=99s rehiring of his favorite Red Bull-chugging
wingman from the 2016 campaign reinforces his ongoing effort to seemingly u=
ndermine his own election chances=E2=80=94go figure. In <i>Blink Twice, Lin=
da</i>, <b>Bill Cohan </b>digs into the financial challenges that <b>Elon M=
usk </b>and <b>Linda Yaccarino </b>have created for themselves at Twitter (=
sorry, X). And in <i>Drahi=E2=80=99s Billion-Dollar Question</i>, <b>Marion=
 Maneker </b>explores the Sotheby=E2=80=99s owner=E2=80=99s fascinating and=
 complex new financing, and what it means not only for his employees but th=
e rival auction houses, artists, and art market writ large.<br/><br/>But if=
 you only have time to read one thing this weekend, I=E2=80=99d turn your a=
ttention to <b>Matt Belloni</b>=E2=80=99s excellent piece on the latest twi=
st in the fate of Paramount, itself a saga featuring multiple second-acters=
=2E As Matt notes in <i>It=E2=80=99s Go-Sh=
op Time for Paramount</i>, liquor s=
cion and former music mogul <b>Edgar Bronfman Jr. </b>is once again sniffin=
g around the company, threatening to outbid Skydance=E2=80=99s
<b>David Ellison </b>and RedBird=E2=80=99s <b>Gerry Cardinale</b>. It=E2=80=
=99s an extraordinary late-stage complexifier, which may end up going nowhe=
re, but nevertheless demonstrates just how much these businesses turn on th=
e insatiable ambitions of the personalities involved. It=E2=80=99s one of t=
he enduring stories of our time, and precisely what you should expect from =
Puck.<br/><br/>Have a great weekend,<br/>Jon<br/></td>
